# `prefetch_index` may create out-of-bounds pointers from safe code

In affected versions, `ptr_hash::util::prefetch_index` was a publicly accessible safe function. It accepted an arbitrary `index` and used it in `s.as_ptr().add(index)` without checking whether the index was in bounds.

Although prefetching an out-of-bounds address is not intended to dereference the pointer, Rust's `ptr.add` requires the resulting pointer to stay within the same allocation or one byte past it. Passing an out-of-bounds index could therefore trigger undefined behavior through safe code.

The public API exposure was removed in `1.0.0`, and the remaining internal pointer calculation was later fixed in `2.0.0-alpha.1` by replacing `ptr.add()` with `ptr.wrapping_add()`.
